##454 infected! Why the number of newly diagnosed cases of "Diamond Princess" cruise liner pneumonia has skyrocketed

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare announced on the afternoon of 17,504 passengers in the test, found 99 people infected with new pneumonia, 70 of them without symptoms. So far 1,723 passengers have been examined and 454 have been infected. While all passengers and crew on board have been quarantined, the number of confirmed cases continues to climb.

According to the Chinese Embassy in Japan, there were more than 300 Chinese passengers on the cruise, including 22 mainland residents, 260 Hong Kong residents, 5 Macau residents and 24 Taiwan residents.

Hong Kong to arrange charter flight to pick up diamond princess passenger

The Security Bureau of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government said on the evening of the 15th that it would arrange a free charter flight to pick up Hong Kong residents quarantined on the "Diamond Princess" in Yokohama, Japan, and return to Hong Kong as soon as possible after being allowed to land.

The HKSAR government will notify the affected Hong Kong residents as soon as possible in accordance with the arrangements made by Japan. To prevent public health risks, the concerned persons will be placed in quarantine centres for 14 days upon their return to Hong Kong.

The President of the Hong Kong Society of Infectious Diseases, Huang Tianyou, said on the 16th that it would be best if passengers on the chartered flight were seated 2m away from each other. Passengers should wear face masks and observe hand hygiene throughout the flight. Symptomatic passengers should be seated at the back of the plane.

According to the Security Bureau of the Hong Kong SAR government, as of the 16th, there were 21 Hong Kong residents among the confirmed cases on board the cruise ship.

US and Canada send chartered planes to pick up their passengers

On the morning of February 17th, two American government chartered planes took off from the Tokyo International Airport to pick up American citizens aboard the Diamond Princess.

About 300 Americans disembarked early Sunday morning and boarded a charter flight to Tokyo International Airport on a Japan Self-Defense Forces bus. The two chartered planes are headed to U.S. air force bases in California and Texas, where passengers will spend 14 days in isolation to determine if they are infected.

According to Japanese media reports, the cruise ship about 40 U. S. citizens confirmed infection with the new coronavirus, these people will stay in Japan for treatment.

Canada's Department of Global Affairs (CGA) issued a statement on the evening of the 15th, said, "the decision was made because of the special circumstances faced by passengers on the cruise ship, as well as to reduce the burden on Japan's health care system. ". "We are working closely with Carnival Cruise Lines and the Japanese government on the evacuation, " the statement said

Those already showing symptoms of the new pneumonia were not allowed to board the plane and would be transferred to the Japanese medical system for treatment, the statement said. Canadian citizens who were picked up on the chartered flight will be sent to a Canadian Department of Transportation Training Facility in Cornwall, Ontario, for a 14-day quarantine.

The number of people infected continues to increase or is related to the structure of the cruise ship

"It is imperative that passengers leave the ship and that those in need receive appropriate medical assistance, " Amesh Adalja, a senior Johns Hopkins University epidemiologist, told reporters, in enclosed spaces such as cruise ships, where people live in close quarters, respiratory infections can easily spread among people.

It is reported that after the whole ship isolation, the number of infected people continued to increase, may be related to the structure of the cruise ship. In general, most cabins are enclosed and the internal ventilation is regulated by the air conditioning, which includes both the external and internal circulation systems. The former regulates the temperature of the cabin after drawing in the air from the sea through an air intake connected to the outside.

It is not known if the diamond princess will be able to turn on the external circulation system in time.

Japan's Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare Katsunobu Kato admitted: "confined space may lead to a new round of infection. The 80-year-old passenger is no longer entirely responsible for the new case. Some of it is due to repeated exposure after a period of time in a confined space."

According to Rick Rubin, professor of Immunology at Harvard, quoted by the CNN, cruises are a closed environment and an ideal place for the spread of infectious diseases.

Expert proposal: Will Suspect case, did not send a patient to separate isolation

Zhou Yongsheng, a professor at the Institute of International Relations at the Foreign Affairs Institute and a doctoral adviser and deputy director of the Center for Japanese Studies, said the continued quarantine on the ship could lead to a further increase in the number of infected people on board. In that case, ISOLATION ON BOARD MAY NOT BE A long-term solution.

Although the Japanese government quarantined all passengers and crew of the diamond princess, there was no separate quarantine for suspected cases and possible latent cases, as well as for ordinary passengers and crew. In the ship's relatively limited space, it would be impractical to separate more than 3,000 passengers, or more than half of them. Therefore, it may be the best solution to consider the transfer of suspected cases from the ship to a land-based Infectious Disease Hospital for isolation, and the isolation of other asymptomatic persons from the ship to the land.

Isolation on land can take many forms. The first option is isolation in an infectious disease hospital. If rooms and beds in infectious disease hospitals are inadequate, hotels far from populated areas can be temporarily rented for observation in isolation. However, during the temporary isolation period, make sure that each potential infected person stays in a separate room and does not move about with each other. Only well-protected health-care workers or service staff can be moved in small amounts to avoid cross-infection.

These measures will help prevent both the continued increase in the number of cases of cross-infection among passengers and crew of the diamond princess and the spread of the epidemic in Japan.
